The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, June 12, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, June 11: The new financial year started on a positive note with industrial growth more than doubling to 9.4 per cent in April. The index of industrial production (IIP), which grew by 4.2 per cent in April 2003, was close to the double-digit mark mainly on account of impressive performance of the electricity, manufacturing and mining sectors. According to the data released by the Central Statistical Organisation, electricity generation showed a growth of 10.7 per cent in April, while manufacturing and mining sectors grew by 9.2 per cent and 9.5 per cent, respectively.																								 New Delhi, June 11: The rate of inflation rose for the third consecutive week to 5.03 per cent for the week ended May 29. The point-to-point wholesale price index (WPI) inflation was up marginally by 0.1 per cent from previous weeks 5.02 per cent. The index was 5.75 per cent in the year-ago period.																								 Mumbai, June 11: The Tata group has renamed Daewoos truck division in South Korea as Tata Daewoo Commercial Vehicle Co Ltd and nominated Ravi Kant as chairman.																								 Chennai, June 11: Export Credit Guarantee Corporation of India (ECGC) will launch an innovative insurance product aimed to protect IT companies from the risks in software exports business, said P. M. A. Hakeem, CMD.																								 Chennai, June 11: Ashok Leyland today announced a 61 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 193.6 crore during 2003-04. The company declared a 75 per cent dividend for shareholders, up from 50 per cent for the year 2002-03.																								 New Delhi, June 11: Titan Industries has reported an 80 per cent jump in net profit at Rs 11.18 crore in 2003-04 against Rs 6.21 crore in the previous fiscal. Total income rose by 20 per cent to Rs 958.52 crore (Rs 797.90 crore).																								 New Delhi, June 11: Fiscal deficit, which was reined in during 2003-04, was relatively higher at Rs 25,998 crore in April. The deficit was relatively lower at 11.2 per cent of the budgeted amount in April 2003, according to the Controller General of Accounts.
